\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Multiplication for 
\series bold
\color black
3 2
\series default
\color inherit
 point symmetry group
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Note that the Cyclic group 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{3}=\{0,1,2\}$
\end_inset

under modulo-3 addition is directly analogous to the 3-fold rotation axes
 point group.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There are only 32 point groups that can be generated by combinations of
 the 1,2,3,4,6,
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{\textrm{1}}$
\end_inset

,m,
\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{\bar{3},\bar{4},\bar{6}}$
\end_inset

symmetry operators.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Every crystal has a set of symmetry elements that is one of these 32 point
 groups or 
\series bold
Crystal Classes.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Crystal classes are further separated into 
\series bold
Crystal Systems
\series default
 based on minimal symmetry requirements.
 (See Hammond Table 3.1, Azaroff Table 1-2)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float table
wide false
sideways false
status open

