\begin_layout Paragraph
Stereographic Projections
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent
Graphic representation of the orientation of planes.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent
The normal to the (hkl) plane (
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{hkl}$
\end_inset

) intersects the reference sphere at the hkl pole.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent
Consider that all hkl planes pass through the center of the reference sphere.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\noindent
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename figures/refsphere.png
	width 30page%

\end_inset


\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Reference Sphere
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent
A plane can be represented by a trace made by the plane through the reference
 sphere.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent
Traces for planes passing through the center of reference sphere are Great
 Circles, or Longitudinal Lines (or Meridians).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Traces for planes perpendicular to diameter of reference sphere, but not
 passing through center are Small Circles or Latitudes (except those at
 the equator).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\noindent
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename figures/sphereplanes.png
	width 30page%

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Reference Sphere with Traces 
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Rather than measuring angles between planes on the surface of the sphere,
 we employ an equi-angular stereographic projection.
 Note: geographers use equal area projection.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent
\align left

\series bold
Angle between two planes
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent
\align left
=Angle between their Great Circles (Angle-True)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent
\align left
=Angle between their Normals
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent
\align left
=Angle along Great Circle connecting their Poles
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Projection plane
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Placed normal to the end of any chosen diameter.
 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

A
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 (See Figure 3.5)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Point of projection
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Other end of chosen diameter.
 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

B
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Note the projections of the Great Circles.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Basic Circle
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
N' E' S' W' = Projection of Great Circle N E S W from plane N E S W with
 normal A B.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Steps for representing the angle for a plane C on a projection:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Plane C
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Normal CP
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Pole P
\end_layout

