\begin_layout Standard
How would Bragg diffraction show that a crystal is cubic? i.e., not orthorhombic
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Use ratio of 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{sin\theta_{100}}{sin\theta_{110}}=\frac{d_{110}}{d_{100}}=\frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}\rightarrow$
\end_inset

if cubic 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If FCC (110) and (100) are forbidden, use (220) and (200) instead.
 
\end_layout

