\begin_layout Section
Special Topics in X-Ray Physics: Extended X-Ray Absorption Fine Structure
 (EXAFS)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
EXAFS: Why Look at photoelectron scattering?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Unlike XRD, EXAFS does not require a crystalline or semi-crystalline material
 to determine a material's structure.
 The probability of dissociating a core photoelectron is related to ionization
 energy, which is different for every element.
 This allows for an element-specific structural probe.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
X-Ray Absorption of Fine Structure (XAFS): an overview
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The incident x ray beam cases a dissociation of core photoelectron.
 The electron 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

feels
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 the surrounding atoms, which yields an absorption spectrum.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

